emale":"1140–Deceased","1164–Female":"1164–Deceased","1175–Male":"1175–Deceased","1110–1176":"1110–1176","1115–Female":"1115–Deceased","Abt 1175":"about 1175","@#DJULIAN@ 1176":"1176","1115":"1115","1135":"1135","1199":"1199","1176":"1176","1110":"1110","1164":"1164","1175":"1175","1163":"1163","1140":"1140","Mauzé-sur-le-Mignon, Niort, Deux-Sèvres, Poitou-Charentes, France":"Mauzé-sur-le-Mignon, Niort, Deux-Sèvres, Poitou-Charentes, France","Mauzé-sur-le-Mignon, Niort, Deux-Sèvres, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France":"Mauzé-sur-le-Mignon, Deux-Sèvres, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France","Mauzé-sur-le-Mignon, Deux-Sèvres, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France":"Mauzé-sur-le-Mignon, Deux-Sèvres, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Mauzé","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin):","habitational name from Mold in Flintshire, Wales, which name derives from Anglo-Norman French <i>mont haut</i> ‘high hill’ (Latinised as <i>mons altus</i>), the Norman name for Bailey Hill on which the castle stood. The name <i>de Montalt</i>, <i>de Mohaut</i> was borne by an Anglo-Norman aristocratic family who acted as castle wardens there but who had their chief seat in Riddlesden in Yorkshire, where the surname proliferated as <i>Mawhood</i> and <i>Maude</i>. In the 17th century one branch of the family acquired lands in Ireland. The Maude baronetcy of Dundrum, Tipperary, was created in 1705 for Robert Maude. His son Cornwallis Maude, Baron de Montalt, was created first Viscount Hawarden in 1793.   Mowatt   is the Scottish form of the name, from a different branch of the same family.","occasionally from Middle English and Norman French female personal name <i>Mahald</i> or <i>Maud</i>, which are Old French forms of ancient Germanic <i>Mahthild</i> (Latinised as <i>Matilda</i>), composed of the Germanic elements <i>maht</i> ‘might, power’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This personal name partly owed its great popularity among Normans in England to the fact that it was the name of the wife (<i>c.</i> 1031–83) of William the Conqueror. Surnames derived from this personal name are found in many forms and spellings, for example,   Mould   and   Moll  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Mall","meanings":["English: from the medieval female personal name <i>Mall</i>, a common form of <i>Mald</i> or <i>Maud</i>. See also   Maude   and   Moll  . It had several pet forms; see   Malin  ,   Malkin  , and   Mallet  .","Indian (northern states): from Sanskrit <i>malla</i> ‘strongman, wrestler’."]},{"name":"Till","meanings":["English: from the Middle English female personal name <i>Till</i>, a pet form of Old French <i>Matild(e)</i> (in its Latin form <i>Matilda</i>), which was an alternative to <i>Maud</i>; see   Maude   2. A diminutive form occurs in   Tillotson  .","North German: variant of   Thiel  ."]},{"name":"Mault","meanings":["English: variant of   Maude   2."]},{"name":"Mowatt","meanings":["Scottish (northeastern): habitational name from Mold (Flintshire), see   Maude   1. The distinctive Scottish form of the name has arisen from a shift of stress in <i>Mohaut</i> from the second to the first syllable. In Caithness and Orkney, the surname is traditionally pronounced ‘Mode’."]},{"name":"Mould","meanings":["English:","from the Middle English female personal names <i>Mold</i>, <i>Moud</i>, or <i>Molt</i>, shortened forms of Anglo-Norman French <i>Mahold</i>, a common variant of <i>Mahald</i>; see   Maude   2.","habitational name from Mold (Flintshire, Wales)."]}]},{"name":"Guillaume","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Germanic.  See  <b>William</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"William","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."]}]},{"name":"IV","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["probably a contracted form of  Jep , vernacular form of   Jacob   ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Guillaume IV de Mauzé was born in 1135, his father, Porteclie I de MAUZÉ, was 25 and his mother, Agnes de Tonnay, was 21. He married Agnes de Maulmont in 1163, in Mauzé-sur-le-Mignon, Niort, Deux-Sèvres, Poitou-Charentes, France. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in 1199, at the age of 64."},"et":{"1135–1199":"1135–1199","1140–Female":"1140–Surnud","1164–Female":"1164–Surnud","1175–Male":"1175–Surnud","1110–1176":"1110–1176","1115–Female":"1115–Surnud","Abt 1175":"umbes 1175","@#DJULIAN@ 1176":"1176","1115":"1115","1135":"1135","1199":"1199","1176":"1176","1110":"1110","1164":"1164","1175":"1175","1163":"1163","1140":"1140","